pull_request.body:
Fixes the lookup time if a user is managed by Icinga for Windows or not in large Active Directory environments, by using `Get-LocalUser` instead.

This Cmdlet is available starting with PowerShell 5.0 and later and only required in general for running Icinga for Windows in JEA context. As JEA is only supported starting with PowerShell 5.0 or later, this will not cause any problems.

In case the command is executed on an older system without the `Get-LocalUser` Cmdlet available, Icinga for Windows will handle all users tested with the new implementation as `not` managed by Icinga for Windows.

Fixes #394

pull_request.body:
- part of https://github.com/ppy/osu-wiki/issues/6233
- [clean output](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/36758269/147963320-f3734293-1d7b-4f35-9a3b-b217027f28c8.png) | [error example 1](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/36758269/147963505-10147756-7757-4440-9d34-588de0e01837.png) | [error example 2](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/36758269/147963549-08f6ceb0-18e8-4854-a8b3-a7cd512b885c.png)

## Remarks

This adds .png, .jpg, and .gif files to the sparse checkout (the only ones ever used, with the exception of some old news posts), which is required for the script to check image links locally. Test times are still only at around or less than 1 minute (about +10 to 15 seconds from quick observation), probably because all images are very small anyway.

This does not check for reference-style (`[text][link]`) or in-article links (`[text](link#heading)`) yet, which I'll probably add later (could also use some more verbose notes that explain why a link is broken).

Non-wiki links are assumed to start with `http`, `mailto:` or `irc:`, which are the only cases currently in the wiki.

All links in master are currently fixed by @TicClick using this in <https://github.com/ppy/osu-wiki/pull/6641>. 

ASC, readme and template articles, as well as links in comments are excluded from the test (they usually contain examples or link to other repo files).

The error message is written in the assumption that you're not a maintainer, so it doesn't actually tell you to edit `redirect.yaml`.

Suggestions on output colours/formatting are welcome.

- part of https://github.com/ppy/osu-wiki/issues/6233
- [clean output](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/36758269/147963320-f3734293-1d7b-4f35-9a3b-b217027f28c8.png) | [error example 1](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/36758269/147963505-10147756-7757-4440-9d34-588de0e01837.png) | [error example 2](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/36758269/147963549-08f6ceb0-18e8-4854-a8b3-a7cd512b885c.png)

## Remarks

This adds .png, .jpg, and .gif files to the sparse checkout (the only ones ever used, with the exception of some old news posts), which is required for the script to check image links locally. Test times are still only at around or less than 1 minute (about +10 to 15 seconds from quick observation), probably because all images are very small anyway.

This does not check for reference-style (`[text][link]`) or in-article links (`[text](link#heading)`) yet, which I'll probably add later (could also use some more verbose notes that explain why a link is broken).

Non-wiki links are assumed to start with `http`, `mailto:` or `irc:`, which are the only cases currently in the wiki.

All links in master are currently fixed by @TicClick using this in <https://github.com/ppy/osu-wiki/pull/6641>. 

ASC, readme and template articles, as well as links in comments are excluded from the test (they usually contain examples or link to other repo files).

The error message is written in the assumption that you're not a maintainer, so it doesn't actually tell you to edit `redirect.yaml`.

Suggestions on output colours/formatting are welcome.

commits.message:
[gdb/testsuite] Handle for loop initial decl with gcc 4.8.5

When running test-case gdb.threads/schedlock-thread-exit.exp on a system with
system compiler gcc 4.8.5, I run into:
...
src/gdb/testsuite/gdb.threads/schedlock-thread-exit.c:33:3: error: \
  'for' loop initial declarations are only allowed in C99 mode
...

Fix this by:
- using -std=c99, or
- using -std=gnu99, in case that's required, or
- in the case of the jit test-cases, rewriting the for loops.

Tested on x86_64-linux, both with gcc 4.8.5 and gcc 7.5.0.

Small indentation fix in eval.c

I noticed that the AdaCore tree had a small divergence in eval.c -- it
had a fix for an indentation problem in binop_promote.  I'm checking
in this small fix as obvious.

Fix regression in page-logging.exp

Simon and Tom pointed out that page-logging.exp failed on their
machines.  Tom tracked this down to the "width" setting.  Since
there's no need in the test to change the width, it seems simplest to
remove the setting.  I confirmed that the test still fails if the fix
is backed out, ensuring that the test is still testing what it
purports to.

Fix use of 'printf' in gdbtypes.c

An earlier patch of mine, commit 64b7cc50 ("Remove
gdb_print_host_address") inadvertently changed a function in
gdbtypes.c to use printf rather than printf_filtered.  This patch
fixes the problem.

[gdb/cli] Improve show logging output

Before commit 3b6acaee895 "Update more calls to add_prefix_cmd" we had the
following output for "show logging":
...
$ gdb -q -batch -ex "set trace-commands on" \
    -ex "set logging off" \
    -ex "show logging" \
    -ex "set logging on" \
    -ex "show logging"
+set logging off
+show logging
Future logs will be written to gdb.txt.
Logs will be appended to the log file.
Output will be logged and displayed.
Debug output will be logged and displayed.
+set logging on
+show logging
Currently logging to "gdb.txt".
Logs will be appended to the log file.
Output will be logged and displayed.
Debug output will be logged and displayed.
...

After that commit we have instead:
...
+set logging off
+show logging
debugredirect:  The logging output mode is off.
file:  The current logfile is "gdb.txt".
overwrite:  Whether logging overwrites or appends to the log file is off.
redirect:  The logging output mode is off.
+set logging on
+show logging
debugredirect:  The logging output mode is off.
file:  The current logfile is "gdb.txt".
overwrite:  Whether logging overwrites or appends to the log file is off.
redirect:  The logging output mode is off.
...
which gives less clear output for some subcommands.

OTOH, it's explicit about whether boolean values are on or off.

The new text seems to have been chosen to match the set/show help texts:
...
(gdb) help show logging
Show logging options.

List of show logging subcommands:

show logging debugredirect -- Show the logging debug output mode.
show logging file -- Show the current logfile.
show logging overwrite -- \
  Show whether logging overwrites or appends to the log file.
show logging redirect -- Show the logging output mode.
...

Make the show logging messages more clear, while still keep the boolean
values explicit, such that we have:
...
$ ./gdb.sh -q -batch -ex "show logging"
logging debugredirect:  off: \
  Debug output will go to both the screen and the log file.
logging enabled:  off: Logging is disabled.
logging file:  The current logfile is "gdb.txt".
logging overwrite:  off: Logging appends to the log file.
logging redirect:  off: Output will go to both the screen and the log file.
...

Tested on x86_64-linux.

  • 5.65.0 - 2021-12-06

    • static evaluation understands undefined now
    • reduce container entry code by a few chars

    • upgrade watchpack for context time info bugfix
